            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-block">
            <h4>💥 Why === Breaks</h4>
            <p>
                When you write <span class="mono">0.1 + 0.2 === 0.3</span>, JavaScript
                evaluates to <strong>false</strong>. The left side is actually
                <span class="mono">0.30000000000000004</span> internally.
                Triple-equals does exact bit-for-bit comparison — no rounding, no tolerance.
                So two values that <em>should</em> be equal are not, causing discount
                checks, threshold comparisons, and equality guards to silently fail.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-block">
            <h4>💰 The Financial Consequence</h4>
            <p>
                Errors accumulate with every addition. A cart with many items can show
                a total that is off by a penny or more. Discount thresholds like
                "free shipping over $50.00" may never trigger even when the true total
                is exactly $50.00. Worse, the bug is <em>invisible</em> — the displayed
                value looks correct because <span class="mono">toFixed(2)</span> rounds
                the display, masking the underlying corruption.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-block">
            <h4>✅ Solution 1: Integer Cents</h4>
            <p>
                Convert every price to <strong>integer cents</strong> immediately on input:
                <span class="mono">Math.round(price * 100)</span>.
                Integers are exact in IEEE 754 up to 2<sup>53</sup>.
                Add cents as integers, then divide by 100 only for display.
                <span class="mono">499 + 299 === 798</span> is always true.
                This is the simplest and most reliable approach for most apps.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-block">
            <h4>✅ Solution 2: Epsilon Comparison</h4>
            <p>
                For cases where you must compare floats, use a tolerance:
                <span class="mono">Math.abs(a - b) &lt; Number.EPSILON</span>.
                <span class="mono">Number.EPSILON</span> is the smallest difference
                JavaScript can distinguish (~2.2e-16). This is useful for geometry
                or physics but still fragile for money — accumulated errors can exceed
                EPSILON. Integer cents is always preferred for financial work.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-block">
            <h4>✅ Solution 3: Decimal Libraries</h4>
            <p>
                Libraries like <strong>decimal.js</strong>, <strong>big.js</strong>, or
                <strong>dinero.js</strong> implement true decimal arithmetic in software,
                bypassing IEEE 754 entirely. They are ideal for complex financial
                calculations involving multiplication, division, tax rates, or currency
                conversion where integer-cents math becomes unwieldy.
            </p>
        </div>

    </div>
