</head>
<body>

<div class="container">

    <h1>🛒 Shopping Cart: Float vs Decimal</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A live demonstration of why floating-point arithmetic breaks money calculations</p>

    <!-- ═══ EXPLANATION BANNER ═══ -->
    <div class="explanation">
        <h2>⚠️ Why Floating-Point Arithmetic Breaks Money Calculations</h2>
        <p>
            Computers store numbers in <strong>binary (base-2)</strong>. Most decimal fractions — like
            <code>0.1</code> or <code>4.99</code> — <strong>cannot be represented exactly</strong> in binary,
            just like <code>1/3</code> cannot be written exactly in decimal. JavaScript's
            <code>Number</code> type uses IEEE 754 double-precision floats, so tiny rounding errors
            accumulate with every arithmetic operation.
        </p>
        <p>
            When a developer uses <code>===</code> to compare a computed total against an expected price,
            those invisible rounding errors cause the comparison to fail — even when the numbers
            <em>look</em> identical on screen.
        </p>
        <div class="code-snippet">
<span class="comment">// 🔴 BROKEN — naive float arithmetic</span>
<span class="keyword">let</span> total = <span class="number">0</span>;
total += <span class="number">4.99</span>;   <span class="comment">// Coffee</span>
total += <span class="number">1.99</span>;   <span class="comment">// Muffin</span>
total += <span class="number">2.49</span>;   <span class="comment">// Juice</span>
console.<span class="fn">log</span>(total);              <span class="comment">// 9.469999999999999  ← not 9.47 !</span>
console.<span class="fn">log</span>(total === <span class="number">9.47</span>);   <span class="comment">// false  ← comparison FAILS</span>

<span class="comment">// 🟢 FIXED — work in integer cents, divide only for display</span>
<span class="keyword">let</span> totalCents = <span class="number">0</span>;
totalCents += <span class="fn">Math</span>.<span class="fn">round</span>(<span class="number">4.99</span> * <span class="number">100</span>);  <span class="comment">// 499</span>
totalCents += <span class="fn">Math</span>.<span class="fn">round</span>(<span class="number">1.99</span> * <span class="number">100</span>);  <span class="comment">// 199</span>
totalCents += <span class="fn">Math</span>.<span class="fn">round</span>(<span class="number">2.49</span> * <span class="number">100</span>);  <span class="comment">// 249</span>
console.<span class="fn">log</span>(totalCents);                  <span class="comment">// 947  (exact integer)</span>
console.<span class="fn">log</span>(totalCents === <span class="number">947</span>);          <span class="comment">// true  ✓</span>
        </div>
        <p>
            <strong>The fix:</strong> Convert every price to <strong>integer cents</strong> immediately
            (<code>Math.round(price × 100)</code>), do all arithmetic in cents, and only divide back
            to dollars when displaying. Integers are represented exactly in binary — no rounding errors.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ SIDE-BY-SIDE CARTS ═══ -->
    <div class="carts-wrapper">

        <!-- ─── BROKEN CART ─── -->
        <div class="cart-card">
            <div class="cart-header broken-header">
                🔴 Broken Cart
                <span class="badge">Naive Float</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cart-body">
                <div class="products" id="broken-products"></div>

                <div class="cart-items" id="broken-items">
                    <div class="empty-msg">No items yet — add some above!</div>
                </div>

                <div class="totals-box">
                    <div class="total-row">
                        <span>Items:</span>
                        <span id="broken-count">0</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="total-row">
                        <span>Raw JS value:</span>
                        <span id="broken-raw" class="raw-value">0</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="total-row grand">
                        <span>Total (displayed):</span>
                        <span id="broken-total">$0.00</span>
                    </div>
