<!-- EXPLANATION PANEL -->
<div class="explanation-panel">
    <h2>📚 Why Floating-Point Fails for Financial Calculations</h2>

    <div class="explanation-grid">
        <div class="exp-card">
            <h3>🔢 The Binary Representation Problem</h3>
            <p>
                JavaScript uses IEEE 754 double-precision binary floating-point.
                Most decimal fractions like <strong>0.1</strong> or <strong>0.3</strong>
                cannot be represented exactly in binary — just as 1/3 cannot be
                written exactly in decimal. The stored value is the closest
                representable binary fraction, which introduces tiny errors.
                These errors accumulate with every arithmetic operation.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="exp-card">
            <h3>⚠️ Why === Makes It Worse</h3>
            <p>
                The triple-equals operator checks for <em>exact</em> bit-for-bit equality.
                When two values should mathematically be equal but were reached via
                different floating-point paths, their binary representations differ
                by tiny fractions. <code>0.1 + 0.2</code> produces
                <code>0.30000000000000004</code>, so <code>=== 0.3</code> returns
                <strong>false</strong> — silently breaking discount checks, cart
                validation, and order totals.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="exp-card">
            <h3>💡 The Integer Cents Solution</h3>
            <p>
                Convert every price to integer cents immediately on input:
                <strong>$4.99 → 499 cents</strong>. Perform all arithmetic
                in integers, which have exact binary representations.
                Only convert back to dollars for display using
                <code>(cents / 100).toFixed(2)</code>.
                Integer arithmetic never drifts, so <code>===</code>
                comparisons on cent values are always reliable.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="exp-card">
            <h3>🏦 What Production Systems Do</h3>
            <p>
                Banks and payment processors store monetary values as integers
                (cents, pence, smallest currency unit). Libraries like
                <strong>Decimal.js</strong>, <strong>Big.js</strong>, or
                <strong>currency.js</strong> provide arbitrary-precision decimal
                arithmetic. Some languages have native Decimal types.
                The key rule: <em>never use native floats for money</em>.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-comment">// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
<span class="code-comment">// ❌ BROKEN: Naive float arithmetic and === comparison</span>
<span class="code-comment">// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
<span class="code-keyword">let</span> total = <span class="code-number">0</span>;
cart.forEach(item => total += item.price);         <span class="code-comment">// drift accumulates</span>

<span class="code-keyword">const</span> tax = total * <span class="code-number">0.085</span>;                         <span class="code-comment">// more drift</span>
<span class="code-keyword">const</span> grandTotal = total + tax;

<span class="code-bad">grandTotal === expectedTotal                        // ← SILENT FAILURE</span>
<span class="code-bad">0.1 + 0.2 === 0.3                                   // false! (0.30000000000000004)</span>
<span class="code-bad">1.005.toFixed(2)                                    // "1.00" not "1.01"!</span>

<span class="code-comment">// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
<span class="code-comment">// ✅ FIXED: Integer cents arithmetic</span>
<span class="code-comment">// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────</span>
