            🎓 Why Float Equality Fails for Financial Calculations
        </div>

        <div class="explanation-grid">
            <div class="explanation-card">
                <div class="explanation-card-title">
                    <span class="step-counter">1</span>IEEE 754 Binary Representation
                </div>
                <p>
                    JavaScript uses 64-bit IEEE 754 double-precision floats.
                    Most decimal fractions <strong>cannot be represented exactly</strong>
                    in binary — just like 1/3 cannot be written exactly in decimal.
                    The number 0.1 in binary is actually
                    0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625.
                    This is baked into the hardware.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="explanation-card">
                <div class="explanation-card-title">
                    <span class="step-counter">2</span>Errors Accumulate
                </div>
                <p>
                    Each arithmetic operation can introduce a tiny rounding error.
                    Add enough prices together and those errors compound.
                    <strong>$4.99 + $3.99 + $1.01</strong> might give you
                    <strong>9.989999999999999</strong> instead of
                    <strong>9.99</strong>. Using === to compare this to 9.99
                    returns <strong>false</strong> even though mathematically
                    it should be true.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="explanation-card">
                <div class="explanation-card-title">
                    <span class="step-counter">3</span>Real Financial Consequences
                </div>
                <p>
                    Discount codes that never apply. Tax calculations off by a penny.
                    Totals that don't match receipts. Refund amounts that are wrong.
                    Inventory reconciliation failures. In high-volume systems,
                    even sub-cent errors multiply into significant losses.
                    Banks and payment processors have strict requirements
                    around exact decimal arithmetic.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

