<!-- ── THEORY ── -->
<div class="theory-box">
  <h2>⚠️ The Problem With Floats in Finance</h2>
  <p>
    JavaScript (like most languages) stores decimal numbers as
    <strong>IEEE 754 double-precision binary floats</strong>.
    Binary fractions cannot exactly represent most decimal fractions.
    <span class="inline-code">0.1</span> in binary is actually
    <span class="inline-code">0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625</span> —
    an infinitely repeating binary sequence that gets rounded to the nearest representable value.
  </p>
  <p>
    When you add several such imprecise values together, the rounding errors accumulate.
    The final result looks almost correct when displayed with
    <span class="inline-code">toFixed(2)</span>, but internally it is something like
    <span class="inline-code">9.969999999999999</span> instead of <span class="inline-code">9.97</span>.
    Using <span class="inline-code">===</span> to compare that against
    <span class="inline-code">9.97</span> returns <span class="inline-code">false</span>
    even though both display identically on screen.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix:</strong> Store and compare prices as <em>integer cents</em>
    (<span class="inline-code">$4.99 → 499</span>), do all arithmetic in integers,
    and only convert back to dollars for display.
    Integers have no rounding error within the safe integer range.
  </p>
</div>

