<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ MAIN EXPLANATION -->
<div class="explanation">
  <h2>📖 Why This Is Catastrophically Wrong in Financial Code</h2>

  <h3>The Core Problem</h3>
  <p>
    Computers store numbers in binary (base 2). Most decimal fractions — like <strong>0.1</strong>,
    <strong>0.99</strong>, <strong>4.99</strong> — have no exact binary representation.
    They get stored as the nearest representable value, which is almost-but-not-quite correct.
    When you do arithmetic, these tiny errors accumulate into visible, wrong results.
  </p>

  <h3>Why === Makes It Worse</h3>
  <p>
    Triple-equals does strict value equality. When you compute a total and compare it to an
    expected price, you're comparing a number that has accumulated floating-point rounding errors
    against a freshly-parsed float that has its own (different) rounding error.
    They are almost never bit-for-bit identical. The comparison silently returns
    <span class="fail">false</span> when any sane person would expect <span class="pass">true</span>.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block"><span class="c-comment">// The developer who "tested it" probably only tested integers</span>
<span class="c-bad">// ❌ BROKEN — naive float approach</span>
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> price1 = <span class="c-number">4.99</span>;
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> price2 = <span class="c-number">4.99</span>;
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> sum    = price1 + price2;          <span class="c-comment">// 9.98? NOPE.</span>
console.<span class="c-func">log</span>(sum);                         <span class="c-comment">// 9.98 (looks ok in console...)</span>
console.<span class="c-func">log</span>(sum === <span class="c-number">9.98</span>);               <span class="c-comment">// false ← SILENT FAILURE</span>
console.<span class="c-func">log</span>(sum.toFixed(<span class="c-number">20</span>));            <span class="c-comment">// 9.98000000000000042633...</span>

<span class="c-keyword">const</span> total = <span class="c-number">0.1</span> + <span class="c-number">0.2</span>;
console.<span class="c-func">log</span>(total === <span class="c-number">0.3</span>);              <span class="c-comment">// false — classic</span>
console.<span class="c-func">log</span>(total);                      <span class="c-comment">// 0.30000000000000004</span>

<span class="c-comment">// In a discount system — catastrophic</span>
<span class="c-keyword">function</span> <span class="c-func">applyDiscount</span>(cart, threshold) {
  <span class="c-keyword">if</span> (cart.total === threshold) {         <span class="c-comment">// NEVER TRUE for most prices</span>
    cart.discount = <span class="c-number">0.10</span>;               <span class="c-comment">// Customer never gets discount</span>
  }
}

<span class="c-good">// ✅ FIXED — store everything as integer cents</span>
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> price1Cents = <span class="c-number">499</span>;               <span class="c-comment">// $4.99 = 499 cents (exact integer)</span>
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> price2Cents = <span class="c-number">499</span>;
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> sumCents    = price1Cents + price2Cents;  <span class="c-comment">// 998 (exact, no error)</span>
console.<span class="c-func">log</span>(sumCents === <span class="c-number">998</span>);          <span class="c-comment">// true ← always correct</span>

<span class="c-comment">// Display by dividing only at the last moment</span>
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> display = <span class="c-func">formatCents</span>(sumCents);  <span class="c-comment">// "$9.98"</span>

<span class="c-comment">// Tax: multiply first, THEN round — never round intermediate values</span>
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> TAX_RATE_BP = <span class="c-number">8875</span>;              <span class="c-comment">// 8.875% in basis points</span>
<span class="c-keyword">const</span> taxCents = <span class="c-func">Math.round</span>(subtotalCents * TAX_RATE_BP / <span class="c-number">1000000</span>);
</div>

  <h3>Real-World Consequences</h3>
  <p>
    This is not hypothetical. Floating-point bugs in financial software have caused
    overcharges, undercharges, failed discount validations, incorrect tax calculations,
    and audit failures. A system processing 10,000 transactions per day with a $0.000001
    error per transaction accumulates $3.65 in unexplained discrepancy per year —
    which triggers regulatory audits. At scale, these errors compound unpredictably.
  </p>

  <h3>The Golden Rules</h3>
  <p>
    <span class="pass">1.</span> Store monetary values as <strong>integer cents</strong> (or smallest currency unit).<br>
    <span class="pass">2.</span> Never use floating-point for money storage or comparison.<br>
    <span class="pass">3.</span> Multiply before dividing. Round only once, at the final step.<br>
    <span class="pass">4.</span> Never use <code>===</code> to compare computed floats. Ever.<br>
    <span class="pass">5.</span> Only convert to decimal display at the moment of rendering to the user.<br>
    <span class="pass">6.</span> Use a dedicated decimal library (decimal.js, big.js) for complex calculations.
  </p>
</div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ FIX STRATEGIES -->
<div class="fix-strategies">
  <div class="strategy">
    <h3>🪙 Strategy 1: Integer Cents</h3>
    <p>Store all prices as integers in the smallest currency unit (cents for USD).
       All arithmetic is exact integer math. Convert to display string only at render time.</p>
    <p class="pros">✅ Simple, zero dependencies, perfectly exact for 2-decimal currencies</p>
    <p class="cons">⚠️ Requires discipline. Breaks for currencies with 3 decimal places (KWD, BHD).</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy">
    <h3>📦 Strategy 2: Decimal.js / big.js</h3>
    <p>Use a library that implements arbitrary-precision decimal arithmetic in software,
       bypassing IEEE 754 entirely. Used by most serious financial applications.</p>
    <p class="pros">✅ Handles any precision, any rounding mode, very readable code</p>
    <p class="cons">⚠️ External dependency, slightly slower (rarely matters for UI code)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="strategy">
    <h3>🏦 Strategy 3: Server-Side Only</h3>
    <p>Never compute final prices in the browser at all. Send quantities to the server,
       compute everything in a language with native decimal types (Python Decimal, Java BigDecimal),
       and return the final amounts.</p>
    <p class="pros">✅ Most secure, server is authoritative, no client-side math bugs</p>
    <p class="cons">⚠️ Requires round-trip for every calculation, UX latency</p>
  </div>
</div>

