  <h2>⚠️ WHY THIS IS CATASTROPHICALLY WRONG — The Full Technical Breakdown</h2>

  <h3>1. IEEE 754 Double-Precision Floating Point Cannot Represent Most Decimals Exactly</h3>
  <p>
    JavaScript (like virtually every language) stores numbers as 64-bit IEEE 754 doubles.
    This format uses binary fractions — powers of 1/2, 1/4, 1/8, etc.
    The decimal value <strong>0.1</strong> cannot be expressed as a finite sum of binary fractions.
    It becomes an infinitely repeating binary sequence that gets rounded to the nearest
    representable value: <strong>0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625</strong>.
    Same for 0.2, 0.3, 4.99, 19.95 — almost every price you will ever use.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Errors Accumulate With Every Operation</h3>
  <p>
    Each addition, subtraction, or multiplication introduces or compounds rounding error.
    A single item at $4.99 is already slightly wrong. Add five items across a cart and
    the error has grown. Multiply by tax rates and it grows again. By the time you reach
    a checkout total the value is guaranteed to be wrong — usually by fractions of a cent,
    but sometimes by whole cents on large orders or after many accumulated operations.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">// What you write:</span>
<span class="bad">0.1 + 0.2</span>
<span class="cmt">// What JavaScript computes:</span>
<span class="bad">0.30000000000000004</span>   <span class="cmt">// NOT 0.3</span>

<span class="cmt">// Your "simple" price comparison:</span>
<span class="bad">4.99 + 4.99 === 9.98</span>   <span class="cmt">// → might be false</span>
<span class="bad">0.1 + 0.2 === 0.3</span>      <span class="cmt">// → false. Always. Every browser. Every time.</span>

<span class="cmt">// Tax calculation on a $99.99 order:</span>
<span class="bad">99.99 * 0.0875</span>         <span class="cmt">// → 8.749125000000001 not 8.749125</span>
  </div>

  <h3>3. === Is Completely Wrong for Float Comparison</h3>
  <p>
    Triple-equals performs strict equality. Two floats that <em>should</em> be equal after
    arithmetic will frequently not be bitwise identical due to accumulated rounding.
    This causes discount thresholds to silently fail, free-shipping triggers to not fire,
    loyalty tier upgrades to be missed, and fraud detection rules to misfire —
    all without any error, any exception, or any warning whatsoever.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">// BROKEN — will silently give wrong answers:</span>
<span class="bad"><span class="kw">function</span> qualifiesForDiscount(total) {
  <span class="kw">return</span> total === <span class="num">50.00</span>;  <span class="cmt">// will NEVER match after float arithmetic</span>
}</span>

<span class="cmt">// BROKEN — rounding display ≠ rounding arithmetic:</span>
<span class="bad"><span class="kw">const</span> display = total.toFixed(<span class="num">2</span>);  <span class="cmt">// "50.00" looks right</span>
<span class="bad"><span class="kw">const</span> charge  = total;             <span class="cmt">// 49.99999999999997 gets charged</span></span>

<span class="cmt">// FIXED — work in integer cents the entire time:</span>
<span class="good"><span class="kw">const</span> toCents = (dollars) => Math.round(dollars * <span class="num">100</span>);
<span class="kw">const</span> toDisplay = (cents) => (cents / <span class="num">100</span>).toFixed(<span class="num">2</span>);

<span class="kw">const</span> price    = toCents(<span class="num">4.99</span>);   <span class="cmt">// 499  — exact integer</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> subtotal = price * qty;      <span class="cmt">// integer multiplication — exact</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> tax      = Math.round(subtotal * <span class="num">875</span> / <span class="num">10000</span>);  <span class="cmt">// integer math</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> total    = subtotal + tax;   <span class="cmt">// exact</span>
total === <span class="num">5000</span>                    <span class="cmt">// safe to use === on integers</span></span>
  </div>

  <h3>4. toFixed() Does NOT Fix The Problem</h3>
  <p>
    A common "fix" is to call <code>.toFixed(2)</code> before comparing or storing.
    This is wrong for two reasons: (a) it returns a <strong>string</strong>, not a number,
    so you must parse it back — introducing yet another conversion step where errors can hide;
    (b) it rounds the <em>display</em> value but the underlying float used in all subsequent
    arithmetic is still wrong. You end up with a cart that <em>displays</em> the right total
    but <em>charges</em> the wrong amount.
  </p>

  <h3>5. The Correct Solution: Integer Cents Throughout</h3>
  <p>
    Store, transmit, and compute every monetary value as an integer number of cents (or the
    smallest currency unit). Only convert to a decimal string at the final display step.
    Integer arithmetic in JavaScript is exact up to 2<sup>53</sup>−1
    (Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER = 9,007,199,254,740,991) which covers any realistic cart total.
    For truly large-scale financial systems use a dedicated Decimal library (decimal.js,
    big.js) or handle all arithmetic server-side in a language with native decimal types.
  </p>
</div>

